The genus
Chirotica Förster, 1869
includes 42 valid species (
) and is found in all biogeographic regions (
). In the Neotropical region, the genus is represented by 14 species, distributed across these following countries: Argentina , Brazil , Cuba , Ecuador , Grenada , Mexico , Saint Vincent , Suriname , Dominican Republic , Trinidad and Tobago , Uruguay , and Venezuela (
). Only three of these are known from Brazil (
), each recorded from a single Brazilian state:
C. nigripes Townes, 1983
(Pará),
C. parallela Townes, 1983
( Pernambuco ) and
C. stigmatica Townes, 1983
( Santa Catarina ). Furthermore, the genus has also been sporadically recorded from the states of Paraná (
) and
Bahia (
Fernandes et al . 2019
)
, but without any species identification.


Chirotica
species

are characterized morphologically by having the genal carina reaching the hypostomal carina above the base of mandible, center of face elevated into a tubercle, clypeus wide and moderately convex, mandibular teeth pointed and of equal sizes, areolet absent, posterior transverse carina of the mesosternum complete, propodeum with entire areas, and areas superomedia and basalis generally confluent (

; 

). As far as currently recorded, they are idiobiont ectoparasitoids parasitoids of larvae or pupae of 
Psychidae
(
Lepidoptera
) (

; 

).

